{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Kirk Urso | image = | fullname = Kirk Jon Urso | birth_date = {{Birth date|1990|03|06}} | birth_place = [[Downers Grove, Illinois]], United States | death_date = {{death date and age|2012|08|05|1990|03|06}} | death_place = [[Columbus, Ohio]], United States | height = {{height|ft=5|in=11}} | position = [[Midfielder]] | youthyears1 = 2005–2007 | youthclubs1 = [[IMG Soccer Academy]] | youthyears2 = 2008–2011 | youthclubs2 = [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's soccer|North Carolina Tar Heels]] | years1 = 2008–2009 | clubs1 = [[Carolina Dynamo]] | caps1 = 25 | goals1 = 4 | years2 = 2010 | clubs2 = [[Chicago Fire Premier]] | caps2 = 16 | goals2 = 5 | years3 = 2012 | clubs3 = [[Columbus Crew]] | caps3 = 6 | goals3 = 0 | totalcaps = 47 | totalgoals = 9 | nationalyears1 = 2007 | nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States U17]] | nationalcaps1 = 2 | nationalgoals1 = 1 }}
'''Kirk Jon Urso''' (March 6, 1990 – August 5, 2012) was an American [[association football|soccer]] player. He played for [[Carolina Dynamo]], [[Chicago Fire Premier]], and [[Columbus Crew]], and also represented the [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States under-17s]]. He died at the age of 22 at the Ohio Health – Grant Medical Center.<ref>{{cite news|title=Columbus Crew mourn passing of midfielder Kirk Urso|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2012/08/05/columbus-crew-mourn-passing-midfielder-kirk-urso|accessdate=August 5, 2012|newspaper=mlssoccer.com|date=August 5, 2012}}</ref>
==Early life== Kirk Jon Urso was born on March 6, 1990 in [[Downers Grove, Illinois]], the younger of Michael and Sandra (née Ceponis) Urso's two children. He had one older brother, Kyle, who played soccer at the [[University of New Hampshire]].
==Career==
===College and amateur=== Urso played [[college soccer]] at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|University of North Carolina]]. He was a 2011 NSCAA All-South Region First Team selection. While at Carolina, he started 80 of the 91 matches (the most in school history) in which he appeared, tallying 15 goals and 24 assists. He scored in each quarter final of the College Cup as a Freshman, Sophomore and Junior, and as a Senior, captained the Tar Heels to a 2011 NCAA Men’s College Cup final 1–0 victory over [[Charlotte 49ers men's soccer|Charlotte]] and was named to the All-Tournament Team. While in college, Urso spent a semester in Europe training with both [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-x.com/2012/08/columbus-crew-player-dies-aged-22/|title=Columbus Crew player dies, aged 22 – Football news|website=www.football-x.com}}</ref>
===Professional=== The [[Columbus Crew]] selected Urso the first round (No. 10 overall) of the [[2012 MLS Supplemental Draft]] and signed him on March 1, 2012. He joined college teammate [[Ben Speas]] with the Crew and made his first appearance during the season opener in Colorado, playing a full 90 minutes. [[File:Kirk Urso Free Kick.jpg|thumb|right|Urso takes a free kick for the Crew against the Red Bulls – April 7, 2012]] He missed May 2012 after sustaining a groin injury.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jardy|first=Adam|title=Urso Sidelined For A Month|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/blogs/covering-the-crew/2012/05/urso-injured.html|accessdate=August 5, 2012|newspaper=Columbus Dispatch|date=May 10, 2012}}</ref>
===International=== Urso played for the United States in the [[FIFA U-17 World Cup]] in 2007. He scored the winning goal in the US vs Belgium game, allowing the US to move on in their group.<ref>{{cite news|title=Columbus Crew says midfielder Kirk Urso, who won an NCAA title with UNC, has died|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/dcunited/columbus-crew-says-midfielder-kirk-urso-who-won-an-ncaa-title-with-unc-has-died/2012/08/05/803165d6-deff-11e1-8d48-2b1243f34c85_story.html|accessdate=August 5, 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=August 5, 2012}}</ref> He also represented USA at the U-20 level.
==Death== On the morning of August 5, 2012, Urso collapsed and fell unconscious at a downtown Columbus establishment and was carried outside. He was taken to a nearby hospital when found by police who happened to be in the area for an unrelated call, where he suffered cardiac arrest. He was pronounced dead at 1:50 AM local time, after several attempts at resuscitation. He was 22 years old.
Autopsy results revealed Urso died from [[arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy]]. <ref>http://www.thenewstribune.com/2012/09/21/2305484/coroner-mls-player-died-of-genetic.html{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
