'''Manuchar III Jaqeli''' ({{lang-ka|მანუჩარ III ჯაყელი}}; 1591–1625), of the [[House of Jaqeli]], was the last [[atabeg]] of the principality of [[Samtskhe-Saatabago|Samtskhe]], nominally ruling between 1607–1625. As a child, he accompanied his father, [[Manuchar II Jaqeli]], when the latter settled at the [[Safavid dynasty|Safavid Iranian]] court, then located at [[Qazvin]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} Later, when the Iranian royal court had already been moved to [[Isfahan]], his mother Elene had been making efforts in order for her son to be able to succeed as the next atabeg,{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=188}} and she discussed the matter at the court with then incumbent Safavid king [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]] (r. 1588–1624), [[Alexander II of Kakheti]], as well as the [[Kingdom of Portugal|Portuguese]] diplomat [[Antonio de Gouvea]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=188}} With Manuchar III living at the court, Elene herself received "virtually nothing" from Abbas I, although she had offered him sovereignty over Samtskhe.{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=188}} After having been confirmed in 1607 as ruler of Samtskhe by Abbas I,{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} Manuchar III continued to fight the [[Ottomans]] in a similar fashion to his father.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} However, he did so until 1608, when due to the circumstances, he was forced to flee to [[Kingdom of Kartli|Kartli]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} Following his father's death in 1614, Manuchar III now officially claimed the title of [[atabeg]] of Samtskhe and made active efforts in order to incite anti-Ottoman sentiments in the area.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} Later, in 1624, he battled against the Ottoman [[pasha]] of [[Erzurum]], and shortly after, he moved again to Kartli.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} There, he supported [[Giorgi Saakadze]] against the Iranians, and was reputable at the [[Battle of Marabda]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|page=379}} In the year 1625, he restarted relations with the Ottomans, who subsequently confirmed him as atabeg of Samtskhe; when he actually returned to Samtskhe however, he was killed (poisoined) by his own uncle [[Beka III Jaqeli|Beka Jaqeli]], better known as [[Beka III Jaqeli|Sefer Pasha]].{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2015|pages=149-50, 379}} Manuchar III was the last Christian ruler of Samtskhe; upon his death in 1625, the Ottomans [[Childir Eyalet|completely incorporated]] the western part of the principality of Samtskhe as a pashalik.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=52}} In 1639, by the [[Treaty of Zuhab]], they also gained the eastern part, which had been under Safavid control.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=85}} The members of the House of Jaqeli, who had been at the head of the principality for centuries, converted to Islam, and remained in power as hereditary [[pasha]]s in the Ottoman service.{{sfn|Suny|1994|page=52}}

